    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Breast Self-Examination", content: "Breast self-examination (BSE) is a self-screening technique in which women systematically palpate breast tissue to detect changes that may indicate pathology. Breast tissue consists of glandular lobules (producing milk), ducts (transporting milk to the nipple), and surrounding adipose and connective tissue — the breast undergoes cyclical changes under estrogen and progesterone influence, with maximal tenderness and nodularity during the luteal phase, making BSE best performed 7-10 days after menstruation onset when hormonal effects are minimal. Breast cancer develops from ductal or lobular epithelial cells through a progression of genetic mutations affecting cell cycle regulation (BRCA1/2, HER2/neu, TP53), evolving from atypical hyperplasia to carcinoma in situ to invasive carcinoma. While current USPSTF guidelines focus on mammographic screening, BSE promotes breast awareness — the nurse should educate patients on the appearance and feel of their normal breast tissue and to report new lumps, skin changes (dimpling, peau d'orange), nipple discharge, or nipple retraction to their healthcare provider promptly." },
